    "summary": "Shenzhen Special Economic Zone, established in 1980 adjacent to Hong Kong, was the flagship experiment of China's economic opening under [[event:3650|Deng Xiaoping's reform program]]. The zone offered foreign investors preferential tax treatment, streamlined customs procedures, and access to cheap Chinese labor, in a territory deliberately designed to test market mechanisms while keeping them geographically contained from the rest of China. Before 1980, Shenzhen was a small fishing village with a population of around 30,000 people.\n\nThe results were staggering by any measure. By 2000, Shenzhen had a population of over seven million and had become one of China's most dynamic manufacturing and technology hubs. Its GDP per capita exceeded that of many developed countries. The Shenzhen model was replicated across coastal China, with additional SEZs established and later extended to broader economic development zones. The city became a symbol of China's economic transformation and the viability of the reform program. It also foreshadowed Shenzhen's later emergence as a global technology hub, home to major companies including Huawei and Tencent.",
